tion called “Double Takes” that elaborates on some of the most popular mafia films and TV shows (e.g. The Godfather and The Sopranos) organized around themes such as adaptation, gender and politics, urban spaces, and performance and stardom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGangster filmszItalyxHistory and criticism. 0aGangster filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMafia in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Crime.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aCamorra.  aCoppola.  aCorleone.  aCosa Nostra.  aGodfather trilogy.  aGomorrah.  aItalian.  aMafia.  aMartin Scorsese.  aThe Sopranos.  abiopic.  afilm history.  amelodrama.  amob.  amovies.  aorganized crime.  awives.1 aAntonello, Pierpaolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayman, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBini, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBisoni, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouchard, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoylan, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasillo, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallero, Jonathan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickie, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Acierno, Pellegrino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarofalo, Piero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGord